t shows off the palette.\n\nNote that this is done according to the current `color_mapping`."]}], "class_variables": [], "instance_variables": [], "inner_classes": [], "documentation": ["An object to represent a color palette.\n\nThis object has 4 'main' colors, 1 'panel' color for each and 3\n'semantic' colors, as well as a 'text' color:\n\n- Main colors are meant to be used to higlight objects on the screen. A\n    good rule of thumb is to use the 60-30-10 rule, which means using your\n    primary color as 60% of any given screen, your secondary color as 30%\n    and finally your tertiary color as 10%.\n\n- Panel colors serve as the backdrop of objects. Generally you want to use\n    matching main and panel colors, so with primary mapping to panel1,\n    secondary to panel2 and so on.\n\n- Semantic colors are meant to catch your eyes and immediately convey a\n    message. We use red to display errors, yellow to display warnings and\n    green to display successful actions. Use sparingly!"]}], "exports": [{"name": "zenith.palette.analogous", "xref": {"fqname": "zenith.palette.analogous", "project": null}}, {"name": "zenith.palette.Palette", "xref": {"fqname": "zenith.palette.Palette", "project": null}}, {"name": "zenith.palette.PalettingFunction", "xref": {"fqname": "zenith.palette.PalettingFunction", "project": null}}, {"name": "zenith.palette.tetradic", "xref": {"fqname": "zenith.palette.tetradic", "project": null}}, {"name": "zenith.palette.triadic", "xref": {"fqname": "zenith.palette.triadic", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "zenith.macros", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "zenith.macros.transform", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "text", "type": {"name": "str", "xref": {"fqname": "functions.str", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "default": null}, {"name": "transformer", "type": {"name": "Callable", "xref": {"fqname": "typing.Callable", "project": "--std--"}, "params": [{"name": "", "xref": null, "params": [{"name": "int", "xref": {"